AGI -&nbsp;<span>&nbsp;Felipe VI will participate for the first time in the oath of the new class of civil guards at the Baeza Academy (Jaén) next 12 April.&nbsp;</span>
&nbsp;
Don Felipe was Prince of the Academy of Guards and Sottufficials in April 2008, two years after King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofía had done so, in both cases even with a flag oath.
In his first visit, the then heir to the throne was named "Civil Guard" honorary, for which he was given a diploma and a hat of the Benemérita, in an act in which he was accompanied by the then Minister of Interior, Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba .
&nbsp;
The new class of civil guards consists of 2.317 students, including 1,585 men and 732 women. The visit of Felipe VI to Baeza takes place in a context marked by the two events that involved the Civil Guard agents in the last two months.&nbsp; The first took place on 9 February in Barbate (Cadice), where two civilian guards died after spurring an anti-drug ship against the motorvedetta on which they were on board.
On 19 March, two other agents died together with four other people when they were hit by a truck while they were at a blockade on the highway between Cadiz and Seville, near the city of Los Palacios.&nbsp; The Baeza Academy, created in 1945, is one of the two educational centers where the agents belonging to the ranks of the submarines, corporals and guards of the armed institute are formed.
&nbsp;

